class ListNode {
    constructor(val, next = null) {
        this.val = val;
        this.next = next;
    }
}

function reverseEvenGroups(head) {
    const dummy = new ListNode(-1, head);
    let prev = dummy, curr = head;
    let count = 0;
    while (curr !== null) {
        count++;
        curr = curr.next;
    }
    curr = head;
    for (let i = 2; i <= count; i += 2) {
        let nextGroupHead = curr;
        for (let j = 0; j < i; j++) {
            if (nextGroupHead === null) break;
            nextGroupHead = nextGroupHead.next;
        }
        let prevGroupTail = prev;
        for (let j = 0; j < i; j++) {
            if (curr === null) break;
            const nextNode = curr.next;
            curr.next = prevGroupTail.next;
            prevGroupTail.next = curr;
            curr = nextNode;
        }
        for (let j = 0; j < i; j++) {
            prev = prev.next;
        }
    }
    return dummy.next;
}
```

    This algorithm works by first initializing a dummy node that points to the head of the linked list and setting variable `prev` to the dummy node. We will maintain pointers `prev` and `curr`, iterating the linked list and calculating the total number of nodes in it. With the total number of nodes, we can now traverse the list again, reversing every even group.

We use a for loop to traverse the linked list, with the variable `i` representing the length of each even group as we iterate through the loop. For each iteration, we update the head of the next group by moving it `i` positions ahead in the list. We maintain a tail reference to the previous group and a new variable `prevGroupTail`. We then replace the node connections within the group to reverse it by detaching the current node, attaching it to the tail, and updating the tail. After reversing the current group, we move the `prev` pointer ahead by `i` positions.

The algorithm returns the modified linked list with even groups reversed.

